      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "Single `sendCommand` abstraction leaks two different transport contracts behind one interface.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
        "related_files": [
          "ui/src/lib/stores/websocket.js",
          "ui/src/lib/stores/data.js",
          "ui/vite.config.js"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "In websocket.js, `sendCommand` branches on `URBIT_MODE`: one path calls `sendPoke(payload)`, the other generates ids/tokens and writes serialized JSON via websocket `SESSION.send`.",
          "Because the mode flag comes from a writable store (`URBIT_MODE` in data.js), call sites cannot infer which transport semantics apply from the function contract.",
          "vite.config.js injects mode flags (`GS_URBIT_MODE`) at build/runtime boundaries, so transport behavior is externally toggled without an explicit transport interface boundary in code."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Introduce explicit transport adapters (e.g., `UrbitTransport`, `WebSocketTransport`) implementing a shared interface with documented request/ack semantics, and inject the selected adapter once during initialization instead of branching in each command send.",
        "reasoning": ""
